WEBVTT

00:11.138 --> 00:11.640
Hi church.

00:11.981 --> 00:12.583
My name is Adam.

00:12.623 --> 00:17.398
I'm one of the pastors here at Reality LA and I'm sure it goes without saying, but I'll say it anyway.

00:17.418 --> 00:18.662
I miss you.

00:18.682 --> 00:20.508
I love you and I miss you.

00:20.548 --> 00:21.170
I miss

00:21.378 --> 00:25.544
Being together on Sundays, I miss seeing everyone in the courtyard.

00:25.564 --> 00:31.012
I miss getting to shake hands and high five and give hugs and see kids running around.

00:31.032 --> 00:43.250
I miss that so much, but I am thankful for the opportunity to at least virtually be with you today, to open God's Word and to be encouraged and comforted together.

00:43.426 --> 00:47.592
I want to start by inviting us into this week's offering.

00:47.992 --> 00:53.359
Part of our worship gathering every week is giving to the Lord for the work of the ministry.

00:53.400 --> 01:04.114
We give because everything we have has come from God and we give because His Kingdom is our greatest priority in this life and in this world.

01:04.450 --> 01:07.214
Normally, we have an opportunity to give physically.

01:07.254 --> 01:11.880
We've always used the push pay app over the last several years.

01:11.920 --> 01:14.484
And so that's a primary way we're giving these days.

01:14.604 --> 01:23.416
So you can get out your cell phone if you haven't already signed up for it and go to the push pay app and you can give to the work of the ministry that way.

01:24.097 --> 01:24.337
All right.

01:24.357 --> 01:31.026
Today, I'm going to be preaching out of the book of Philippians chapter one versus 27 through 30.

01:32.354 --> 01:41.683
So Philippians chapter one, 27 through 30 says, only let your manner of life be worthy of the gospel of Christ.

01:42.404 --> 01:56.557
So whether that I come and see you or am absent, I may hear of you that you are standing firm in one spirit with one mind striving side by side for the faith of the gospel and not frightened in anything by your opponents.

01:57.298 --> 02:01.842
This is a clear sign to them of their destruction, but of your salvation,

02:02.082 --> 02:17.503
And that from God, for it has been granted to you that for the sake of Christ, you should not only believe in Him, but also suffer for His sake, engaged in the same conflict that you saw I had and now hear that I still have.

02:18.344 --> 02:18.785
Let's pray.

02:21.068 --> 02:31.442
Jesus, I pray for this time that we have in your word, God, that you would comfort, that you would encourage

02:31.778 --> 02:36.223
Lord, that you would convict and challenge, that you would use this time as you see fit.

02:36.964 --> 02:57.810
As we're experiencing our own variety of hardships and trials, as we have opportunity to hear Paul's instruction to this church, Lord, I pray that these words would fall upon our hearts in our situation, in our hardships, in our grief, to bring comfort

02:57.890 --> 03:00.894
and to challenge us to live lives worthy of the gospel.

03:01.034 --> 03:01.895
So we give you this time.

03:02.416 --> 03:03.898
We pray these things in Jesus name.

03:04.499 --> 03:04.779
Amen.

03:06.221 --> 03:06.522
Amen.

03:07.523 --> 03:12.790
Well, recently my wife and I were reading a short devotion to our kids before bed.

03:13.250 --> 03:16.555
It was about diamonds and how diamonds are made.

03:16.615 --> 03:21.522
You know, a little bit of pressure, well, a lot of pressure and a lot of heat over time.

03:21.542 --> 03:27.890
And you end up with one of the most, one of the strongest and most beautiful materials on earth.

03:28.514 --> 03:35.582
But the short story made this comparison between diamonds and our faith when tested by difficult circumstances.

03:36.162 --> 03:40.787
So our faith when tested by trials produces something strong and beautiful.

03:41.588 --> 03:46.373
And I'll be honest with you, at the time, I was a little bit frustrated with what we were experiencing in life.

03:46.473 --> 03:48.235
It was not what I wanted to hear.

03:48.255 --> 03:51.859
I didn't want God to give me perspective.

03:51.879 --> 03:54.042
I wanted God to just make it all go away.

03:55.023 --> 03:58.066
But it's actually what I needed to hear that night.

03:58.530 --> 04:00.292
I needed an eternal perspective.

04:00.973 --> 04:04.977
I needed to remember that God is with me and my family.

04:05.057 --> 04:07.660
I needed to remember that he's making something beautiful.

04:08.981 --> 04:16.169
You see, the Apostle Paul was able to rejoice in his own hardships because he saw what God was doing.

04:16.729 --> 04:18.871
He saw God doing remarkable things through it.

04:18.891 --> 04:25.138
And here in our passage, he turns a corner to talk about the circumstances that this church in Philippi is facing.

04:25.698 --> 04:29.246
And he's going to lead them toward an eternal perspective as well.

04:30.168 --> 04:32.634
But at the same time, he's going to challenge them.

04:33.516 --> 04:36.563
So comfort and exhortation are not mutually exclusive.

04:37.244 --> 04:45.202
It's my hope for us today is that we would be comforted, where we need to be comforted, and we would be challenged, where we need to be challenged.

04:45.954 --> 04:51.162
Thus far in the book of Philippians, Paul has spoken openly about his own trials and difficulties.

04:51.202 --> 04:54.988
But here we get a glimpse into the life of the believing community.

04:55.008 --> 04:58.834
We get a glimpse into the struggle of the church in Philippi.

04:59.535 --> 05:02.340
Apparently, they're experiencing opposition.

05:03.341 --> 05:09.310
And if that wasn't enough, this opposition seems to be creating tension within their little community.

05:10.212 --> 05:11.634
We need to be aware of

05:11.778 --> 05:19.307
how trials that we're facing as a community today can result in division inside the church, but it doesn't have to.

05:20.068 --> 05:23.312
And so Paul's words here are important for us today.

05:24.374 --> 05:28.659
He says, only let your manner of life be worthy of the gospel of Christ.

05:29.680 --> 05:40.754
Now the temptation you may have as you hear this is to hear Paul saying that you need to make yourself worthy in order to receive the gospel, but that's

05:40.930 --> 05:42.673
how our world works.

05:42.693 --> 05:48.081
You have to prove yourself worthy and then you'll receive the promotion or the degree or whatever else it might be.

05:48.381 --> 05:50.344
But this is not how the gospel works.

05:51.226 --> 05:57.075
See, Jesus died for sinners to give them life and forgiveness and freedom from their sin.

05:57.375 --> 06:03.785
And so the command to live worthy of this is a call to live according to what we have received.

06:04.707 --> 06:09.554
If we've been given freedom from sin, then we need to live free from sin.

06:09.954 --> 06:17.522
If we have been reconciled to God, then we should live in unity as we've also been reconciled to one another.

06:18.343 --> 06:19.364
We need to change.

06:19.785 --> 06:26.332
We do not need to change our lives in order to receive the gospel, but if we receive the gospel, it will change our lives.

06:27.052 --> 06:36.703
Our circumstances may not change, but our character and our life within circumstances must reflect the gift of grace that we've received.

06:36.723 --> 06:39.826
And times of trial and suffering are not

06:40.066 --> 06:40.827
an off-season.

06:41.688 --> 06:46.473
The season in Philippi, while Paul was absent from them, was not an off-season.

06:47.454 --> 06:54.441
It'd be tempting for the church in Philippi to relax their efforts until Paul was released from prison and came to visit.

06:55.181 --> 06:56.843
But Paul says not to wait.

06:57.744 --> 06:58.785
He says, do this now.

06:58.805 --> 07:02.869
He says, I want to hear about you, even if I'm absent.

07:04.070 --> 07:07.634
It's tempting for us in this season, maybe, the season of pandemic.

07:07.938 --> 07:18.635
and stay at home orders and all of the other difficult things going on in life to maybe tempting to relax our efforts as a church or as disciples to wait for the day when life returns to normal.

07:20.057 --> 07:21.319
But what does that mean for this time?

07:21.339 --> 07:22.501
What is that saying about now?

07:23.823 --> 07:25.305
Is this time any less important?

07:25.726 --> 07:26.267
Of course not.

07:27.148 --> 07:33.298
In fact, I think we need to pay extra close attention to seasons of trial.

07:33.762 --> 07:38.346
because it's in our trials that our faith is strengthened and our character revealed.

07:38.406 --> 07:42.991
It's in moments of testing and trials that we see who we truly are.

07:43.171 --> 07:54.442
The character that we cultivate in peaceful seasons is harvested in trial and we have an opportunity to look at that fruit and to learn from what's exposed and to respond accordingly.

07:55.643 --> 08:02.770
Difficulty is not an excuse to run deeper into our vices or to press pause on our spiritual formation.

08:03.010 --> 08:05.793
difficulty is not an excuse to justify our sin.

08:05.853 --> 08:08.035
It's the time to press in.

08:08.095 --> 08:13.721
The things that are hidden in our hearts, hidden even from us, they're exposed in times like these.

08:14.361 --> 08:17.544
We have the opportunity to bring it to the Lord, no matter what it is.

08:17.584 --> 08:25.752
As one of your pastors, I wanna tell you that while we may be physically distant right now, we are hearing of you.

08:25.793 --> 08:31.378
And the ways that many of you are responding in this season, specifically regional prayer,

08:31.458 --> 08:39.066
You all logged into yet another Zoom meeting because you value the desperation for prayer.

08:39.107 --> 08:40.508
It's important to us.

08:41.369 --> 08:49.518
And also the community group leaders and deacons and various other people who are taking on the responsibility of facilitating small digital gatherings throughout the city.

08:49.919 --> 08:55.285
It's challenging and difficult to rest and receive when you're focused on caring for those around you.

08:55.605 --> 08:56.626
And it's beautiful.

08:57.250 --> 09:21.106
For those of you who are looking and reaching out for resources to read or to guide you through personal spiritual formation during this time, for those of you who are pressing into Jesus, for those of you who are taking time to care for people, those of you who are being generous with others who have fallen on difficult financial times, they're those on the front lines, those who got into healthcare in the first place to partner with God in his work of healing.

09:21.538 --> 09:29.731
For the parents who have all added the title teacher to their already overwhelming list of responsibilities, and so many more, we hear about you.

09:30.492 --> 09:31.413
And I'm proud of you.

09:31.453 --> 09:37.182
I'm thankful for your pursuit of a life worthy of the gospel that you've received.

09:38.184 --> 09:41.929
You're doing the very thing that Paul was urging the Philippian believers to do.

09:42.791 --> 09:46.697
But there are some specific things that Paul calls the church to pursue.

09:46.757 --> 09:50.162
And these are things that we should remember as well.

09:51.650 --> 10:04.950
Specifically, Paul says, I want to hear of you that you are standing firm in one spirit with one mind striving side by side for the faith of the gospel and not frightened in anything by your opponents.

10:06.051 --> 10:14.444
For Paul, this is what it means for the Philippians to live worthy of the gospel, unity, diligence, and courage.

10:15.125 --> 10:17.288
I'm gonna break those three things down a bit.

10:18.390 --> 10:21.234
Unity is a primary theme throughout all of Paul's letters.

10:21.634 --> 10:23.716
Philippians isn't any different.

10:23.736 --> 10:34.828
The world will always provide reasons for chaos and disunity, but the gospel is about reconciliation and those who will not be reconciled and unified are not walking in step with it.

10:36.029 --> 10:42.937
We're going to get into unity more in the coming weeks, but today it's important to recognize that there is a lot of division in the world right now.

10:43.638 --> 10:47.762
There was division before the outbreak, and it's only increased since.

10:48.002 --> 10:51.626
And unfortunately, this division runs through churches everywhere.

10:52.487 --> 11:04.860
However, while we are allowed to disagree with one another about many things, we can never allow differences between brothers and sisters in Christ to bring division to the body of Christ.

11:05.661 --> 11:10.806
We've been reconciled to God and to one another, and we need to live in light of that gospel truth.

11:11.667 --> 11:14.610
And this is not some passive sentimental unity.

11:15.394 --> 11:16.896
It's something that's fought for.

11:16.956 --> 11:21.101
It's an active commitment to stand firm together, as Paul says.

11:21.161 --> 11:26.167
And it's not only a commitment to one another, we're to strive alongside one another.

11:26.488 --> 11:31.835
We are to not only be united, but diligent in our striving and pursuit of the gospel.

11:32.155 --> 11:33.236
There's work to be done.

11:34.177 --> 11:37.982
See, diligence is another thing that Paul needs to remind the church about.

11:38.683 --> 11:44.210
When opposition or difficulty comes, we can be tempted to retreat, to lay low until it all blows over.

11:44.482 --> 11:47.786
But Paul says that we must be ready in season and out of season.

11:48.227 --> 11:52.151
We must be side by side striving for the faith of the gospel.

11:52.692 --> 11:58.019
This is a diligence to cling to the gospel for ourselves as well as to share it with others.

11:58.920 --> 12:03.345
To circumstances may not be great in Philippi, but there is still work to be done.

12:04.466 --> 12:07.230
Church, don't let your guard down in this season.

12:07.931 --> 12:13.938
Though your life probably looks remarkably different in this season, you're invited by God to press into him.

12:14.306 --> 12:22.115
to look to his word, to devote yourself to prayer, and to share the good news of Jesus with people in this city who are desperate for some good news.

12:23.237 --> 12:27.822
And as we do, we're gonna experience opposition, but we have to have courage.

12:28.703 --> 12:30.345
This is the third thing that Paul mentions.

12:30.685 --> 12:32.868
We've been talking a lot about courage lately.

12:33.288 --> 12:35.731
We wanna be people driven by faith and not fear.

12:36.552 --> 12:41.458
Likewise, Paul wants the believers in Philippi to not be frightened by their opponents.

12:41.826 --> 12:44.690
Paul was arrested in Philippi for preaching the gospel.

12:45.131 --> 12:48.736
As he writes this, he was put in prison in Rome for preaching the gospel.

12:49.096 --> 12:50.358
Others are being persecuted.

12:50.659 --> 12:54.985
Again, it would be tempting to retreat, but Paul says, stand firm together.

12:55.365 --> 12:56.167
Be diligent.

12:56.507 --> 12:57.428
Do not be afraid.

12:58.470 --> 13:02.796
Remember last week that Paul says, to live is Christ and to die is gain.

13:03.357 --> 13:09.746
It's good to live and to labor for God's glory, but we also don't need to fear even the worst fate

13:09.858 --> 13:13.542
For the believer, death is a new beginning of life with Jesus.

13:14.482 --> 13:18.586
But faith and lack of fear doesn't mean that we can be foolish or reckless.

13:19.207 --> 13:23.091
I'd like to think that I trust Jesus, but I still wash my hands when I get home from the grocery store.

13:23.591 --> 13:27.835
I'd like to think that I trust Jesus, but that doesn't mean I let my kids play unsupervised in the street.

13:28.596 --> 13:33.881
So the call to not be afraid doesn't mean that we don't consider danger or care about the well-being of others.

13:34.482 --> 13:38.866
It means not backing down from our faith in Jesus when the heat is turned up.

13:39.650 --> 13:45.616
Remember, this is all about the community of disciples in Philippi, standing firm together, laboring together.

13:45.876 --> 13:51.082
So a refusal to back down from their opponents is also a unity in the faith.

13:51.862 --> 13:56.647
Unity, diligence, and courage, three things that we desperately need today.

13:58.149 --> 14:03.695
Paul says that the life characterized by these things is a double edged sword.

14:04.495 --> 14:07.058
It's a sign of two things to their opponents.

14:07.458 --> 14:13.105
It's a sign of their opponent's destruction, but also a sign of the church's salvation.

14:13.946 --> 14:25.921
Their unwavering faith and their unity in the midst of trial, their willingness to live and to die for what they believe was, in Paul's mind, a very powerful statement to the world.

14:26.682 --> 14:32.690
Like the Roman centurion standing by when Jesus died, his words were, surely this was the Son of God.

14:33.346 --> 14:45.023
And when people observing your faith in the midst of carrying your own cross, may they be able to say, surely Jesus is the Son of God because no one can face something like this by human strength.

14:45.063 --> 14:47.467
Their God must be with them.

14:49.069 --> 14:54.638
Our conduct in life, but especially in seasons like this will be seen and remembered.

14:55.359 --> 15:00.306
It's in seasons like this pandemic when our faith and our character are put to the test.

15:00.642 --> 15:06.592
And if we walk in a manner worthy of the gospel, then our faith is strengthened and our character revealed.

15:07.072 --> 15:12.041
And the world looking in will see the power of God in our lives and in our communities.

15:12.301 --> 15:14.164
And they will be forced to reckon with it.

15:15.286 --> 15:21.817
My dad met Jesus two weeks after being diagnosed with cancer and the Holy Spirit completely transformed him.

15:22.638 --> 15:26.264
His attitude toward life and other people became so full of joy.

15:26.304 --> 15:27.666
Nobody.

15:27.906 --> 15:39.179
could understand how a man with such a diagnosis, who was always, to be honest with you, a little bit grumpy, no one understood how that man could become so full of joy and optimism.

15:39.239 --> 15:47.048
To this day, there are members of my family that get upset when I use my dad's life as an example of how the gospel transforms.

15:47.668 --> 15:52.754
They get angry because they can't explain it and they don't want to be the truth to be true.

15:54.242 --> 16:00.492
One of the evidences that we are living lives worthy of the gospel is that those around us will notice.

16:01.353 --> 16:06.781
It's not only about what we say that we believe, it's also about what others see that we believe.

16:07.703 --> 16:11.548
And trials create opportunities for others to see Christ in us.

16:12.129 --> 16:17.037
And Paul says that our lives in trial is a sign to the world.

16:20.041 --> 16:23.026
The church in Philippi is experiencing difficulty.

16:23.522 --> 16:28.127
There's opposition from the outside and temptations toward fear and disunity on the inside.

16:28.928 --> 16:38.540
Paul says that the gospel empowers a life of unity with other believers, a diligent pursuit and proclamation of the gospel and courage in the face of opposition.

16:38.940 --> 16:40.402
We need this word today.

16:41.683 --> 16:47.751
But Paul hasn't yet addressed how the church should understand the reality of their suffering.

16:48.712 --> 16:50.674
So he moves from this exhortation.

16:51.298 --> 16:58.230
to a theological reflection that ties this whole passage together and is going to lead us into what he'll say in the next chapter.

16:58.290 --> 17:03.900
He uses this as an opportunity to address the nature of suffering in the Christian life.

17:05.122 --> 17:13.938
See Paul's experience of suffering as a Christian began at his conversion when he was suddenly blinded after encountering the resurrected Jesus.

17:14.434 --> 17:25.285
He'd also been beaten a number of times, stoned and left for dead, shipwrecked more than once, and he had some sort of ongoing physical ailment that he called the thorn in his flesh.

17:26.065 --> 17:29.409
And now he's in prison, and he's awaiting what could be his death sentence.

17:30.109 --> 17:34.794
He had plenty of opportunity to reflect on his experience in light of the gospel and the character of God.

17:35.154 --> 17:40.740
He knows that there are mistakes that we can make and false conclusions we can jump to if we're not careful.

17:40.760 --> 17:43.122
I wanna outline just three

17:43.202 --> 17:46.249
wrong views of suffering in light of God.

17:46.269 --> 17:56.932
The first is to think that suffering is purely bad, it must be avoided at all cost, and sometimes God punishes with suffering because he's displeased with us.

17:57.774 --> 17:59.858
But that's just not the case, and we'll explain why.

18:00.738 --> 18:06.805
The second one is that suffering is actually a good thing because it can accomplish good.

18:06.925 --> 18:11.510
And so we are to celebrate suffering when it comes, but that's ridiculous.

18:11.910 --> 18:16.996
This mistakes the opportunity that God provides through suffering with the suffering itself.

18:17.276 --> 18:18.417
And they're not the same thing.

18:19.538 --> 18:25.064
And a third false conclusion that we can add to these would be that suffering is just a part of life.

18:25.385 --> 18:26.726
There's nothing you can do about it.

18:27.287 --> 18:29.349
And God's not involved at all.

18:29.389 --> 18:30.290
So just deal with it.

18:31.010 --> 18:32.211
all of these fall short.

18:32.792 --> 18:41.282
They're significantly shallow attempts to make sense of our experiences, but Paul's theology has depth to it.

18:41.322 --> 18:43.665
His theology of suffering is profound.

18:44.386 --> 18:48.992
For Paul, in one sense, suffering is part of life in a wounded world.

18:49.632 --> 18:54.418
But God does not allow anything that takes place in his world to go to waste.

18:54.594 --> 18:58.680
He doesn't afflict his people with suffering out of his displeasure with them.

18:59.000 --> 19:01.163
If we're in Christ, then he's pleased with us.

19:01.644 --> 19:04.188
And Christ has taken our punishment in our place.

19:04.508 --> 19:08.934
However, he will use the suffering we experience for his purposes.

19:09.475 --> 19:14.602
God hijacks our circumstances and his spirit directs our hearts toward him.

19:14.903 --> 19:18.187
What may have been meant for evil, God will use for good.

19:19.068 --> 19:22.994
And in this way, there is something to receive in suffering.

19:23.906 --> 19:30.574
And so Paul says that not only has our faith in Jesus been granted to us, but also our suffering.

19:31.054 --> 19:37.963
Literally this word translated granted comes from the same root as the word translated grace.

19:38.583 --> 19:40.145
We've been graced.

19:40.165 --> 19:42.027
We've been gifted with suffering.

19:42.848 --> 19:51.058
Not because it's a good thing, but because Christ is revealed through us to the world when we suffer well.

19:52.482 --> 20:01.099
Through suffering together, striving for the gospel with courage, we give a wounded world a picture of what Jesus has done to bring healing.

20:02.021 --> 20:08.634
And the healing he brings is spiritual, it's physical, it's emotional, it's relational, it's all encompassing.

20:09.035 --> 20:14.706
The healing he offers in his blood is healing for our minds and our hearts and our communities.

20:14.946 --> 20:18.972
It's a promise of healing that changes the way we face illness and disease.

20:19.293 --> 20:24.400
And it's a healing that changes the way we face political disunity and racial injustice.

20:25.342 --> 20:30.389
Your life can be an opportunity for others to look at and say, this is what God is like.

20:31.130 --> 20:34.355
Cause Jesus doesn't punish with violence and suffering.

20:34.636 --> 20:36.899
He ran head on into suffering.

20:37.179 --> 20:41.726
He took on the cross in our place and set us free from eternal suffering.

20:42.427 --> 20:44.210
Living in light of this truth.

20:44.450 --> 20:48.275
Following Jesus in his example means that we can stand firm.

20:48.596 --> 20:57.067
We can stand united and we can boldly proclaim Christ with incredible courage and peace even in the midst of a storm, even in the heart of 2020.

20:57.287 --> 21:04.818
So the way forward in suffering and difficulty is the same way forward in all of our circumstances.

21:05.499 --> 21:12.108
We don't look at our circumstances and analyze them and try to figure them out like a puzzle and conquer them or find the right answer.

21:12.168 --> 21:13.970
We look to Jesus.

21:14.402 --> 21:16.904
We look to the one who suffered and died and was raised again.

21:17.525 --> 21:22.410
We follow a Savior who was a man of sorrows and acquainted with grief, as the prophet said.

21:22.450 --> 21:27.795
As disciples of a crucified Lord, we're called to pick up our cross and follow Him.

21:28.496 --> 21:32.920
We're to embrace suffering, to embrace loss and to grieve.

21:33.681 --> 21:40.448
As Jesus wept outside of His friends Lazarus' tomb, we feel the full weight of pain in this world.

21:41.469 --> 21:42.610
Not as a good thing,

21:42.882 --> 21:53.233
But as part of a life that Christ himself experienced and showed us the way through, every loss, every death deserves to be grieved.

21:54.114 --> 22:02.063
Before it's news, before it's a topic of discussion, before it's just another statistic, it's a tragedy.

22:02.884 --> 22:12.594
And we owe it to those who are dying, whether by COVID or by racial violence, we owe it to each individual as an image bearer of God to show them the dignity

22:12.866 --> 22:14.007
by grieving for them.

22:14.949 --> 22:16.510
You see, statistics can be argued.

22:17.271 --> 22:20.415
News can be debated, but grief unites.

22:21.216 --> 22:24.320
And as a united people, we need to grieve together.

22:24.680 --> 22:34.532
And we need to grieve the systems and the structures and the brokenness, the woundedness in this world that's allowed to continue, that causes us to repeatedly face these losses and these tragedies.

22:35.513 --> 22:39.378
And then united together, we strive together for the sake of the gospel.

22:39.458 --> 22:44.566
courageously bringing healing and seeking an end to suffering in Jesus' name.

22:45.708 --> 22:53.580
Suffering is another opportunity to follow Jesus and show the world what he is like as we embrace it for the healing of others.

22:56.144 --> 22:59.870
Is our conduct in life worthy of the gospel?

23:00.551 --> 23:04.818
Can you draw a straight line between your faith in Jesus and your priorities?

23:05.410 --> 23:14.142
Specifically, can you make a direct connection between your faith in Jesus and your conduct during this pandemic or in the midst of racial tensions?

23:15.104 --> 23:16.085
Are we suffering well?

23:16.926 --> 23:19.590
Are we willing to suffer at all on behalf of others who are hurting?

23:20.732 --> 23:23.456
Can we point to our pursuit of unity with other believers?

23:23.756 --> 23:25.819
Are we diligent in our pursuit of Jesus?

23:26.159 --> 23:30.866
Are we courageous in our faith, honest about our grief, our anger, our loneliness?

23:31.618 --> 23:36.565
Now is time more than ever to fight for unity and the relationship that God has blessed you with.

23:36.945 --> 23:43.634
Now is time more than ever to share the gospel, the news, the good news to people desperate to hear it.

23:44.215 --> 23:45.497
Now is time to grieve.

23:46.318 --> 23:48.060
But now is also a time to take courage.

23:49.162 --> 23:53.308
Jesus promised that we would have trouble in this life, but he told us we could take heart.

23:53.748 --> 23:56.111
We could take courage because he's overcome the world.

23:57.593 --> 24:00.978
The worst thing that this world can throw at us is death.

24:01.826 --> 24:04.595
Death and violence is the enemy's greatest weapon.

24:05.457 --> 24:13.362
Death and violence is always to be grieved, and yet Jesus has disarmed the devil by proving that death can't hold him.

24:13.922 --> 24:14.843
He's overcome.

24:15.324 --> 24:32.564
And the reason this is encouraging for us, the reason that His overcoming the world gives us the ability to take heart is because we follow as those who follow this victorious King, those who've been united to our risen Savior, we also walk in His victory.

24:33.245 --> 24:41.234
In Christ, we have and we will overcome, even if death should take us, like Jesus, we will be raised in glory.

24:42.242 --> 24:46.868
So let us live our lives today in a manner worthy of this eternal truth.

24:47.749 --> 24:58.283
As we do, we'll find ourselves and our communities like a diamond being formed into something beautiful, something that reflects the glory of our Savior.

24:58.984 --> 24:59.445
Let's pray.

25:00.887 --> 25:03.010
Jesus, this is what we ask of you today.

25:04.131 --> 25:09.298
God, to change our hearts, to empower us by your spirit,

25:09.506 --> 25:24.147
to unite us together, to be diligent side by side, striving for the gospel, to proclaiming the good things that you've done, the salvation that you've brought to us, Lord, and to be courageous, to be bold in our faith.

25:25.069 --> 25:30.717
But there are people in this world who are desperate for good news, and that is exactly what you've given us.

25:31.077 --> 25:32.519
That's exactly what we have.

25:32.760 --> 25:34.763
We have good news for a broken world.

25:35.644 --> 25:37.106
Let that truth

25:37.314 --> 25:41.947
that eternal truth that we belong to you and that our future is secure.

25:42.308 --> 25:48.946
Let that truth transform the way that we live today, even in difficulty, even in sorrow.

25:48.994 --> 25:51.777
Even in grief, Lord, would you heal our wounds?

25:52.017 --> 25:54.580
Would you comfort those who are suffering?

25:54.880 --> 26:03.390
God, and would you empower us to be people that reflect who you are when we go through tragedy, when we go through difficulty?

26:03.650 --> 26:18.386
God, I pray for the people of Reality LA, for the believers in this city, that when the world looks in on us and on our unity and on the way we suffer well, I pray that they would see a glimpse of what our God is like.

26:18.818 --> 26:22.880
We pray all of these things, Lord, for your glory and the good of your people.

26:23.644 --> 26:23.986
Amen.

